The '''Colonial Society of Massachusetts''' is a [[Non-profit organization|non-profit]] educational foundation, founded in 1892, and established for the study of the history of [[Massachusetts]]. The period of study is from its settlement through the early nineteenth century. It is a member of the [[New England Regional Fellowship Consortium]]. 

The society publishes documents regarding the early history of Massachusetts and convenes scholarly conferences.  Its education efforts include encouraging the study of colonial Massachusetts in schools, conducting workshops for teachers, and promoting the sharing of research amongst graduate students. It sponsors ''[[The New England Quarterly]]'' in partnership with [[Northeastern University]] and the [[Massachusetts Historical Society]]. 

Its headquarters are located at 87 Mount Vernon Street on [[Beacon Hill, Boston#Mount Vernon Street|Boston's Beacon Hill]]. In the early twentieth century, some of its meetings were held at the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]].<ref name="TheAcademy">{{cite book|title=Daedalus: proceedings of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences|publisher=The Academy|date=1913|edition=Digitized Apr 7, 2006|volume= 48|pages=779|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9Q0DAAAAIAAJ&pg=RA3-PA779&dq=Colonial+Society+of+Massachusetts&lr=&ei=5WTaSufVJIfMlQSKqNWRCA&client=firefox-a#v=onepage&q=Colonial%20Society%20of%20Massachusetts&f=false}}</ref>

==Awards==
The society's Whitehill Prize in Early American History honors [[Walter Muir Whitehill]], the society's editor from 1946 to 1978/

